HB541 INTRODUCED
29
30 A BILL
31 TO BE ENTITLED
32 AN ACT
33
34 Relating to primary elections; to establish the
35 Safeguard Alabama Voter Engagement (SAVE) Act; to require
36 electors to register their party affiliation in order to vote
37 in primary elections and to provide for deadlines to register
38 party affiliation; to amend Sections 17-13-1 and 17-13-7,
39 Code of Alabama 1975, to prohibit electors registered with a
40 political party from voting a different political party ballot
41 at a primary election or primary runoff election; to require
42 the Secretary of State to retain certain voter history
43 information as a public record; to amend Section 17-3-52, Code
44 of Alabama 1975, to require the Secretary of State to revise
45 the voter application form to allow for party registration; to
46 repeal Section 17-13-7.1, Code of Alabama 1975, which
47 prohibits crossover voting between a primary election and
48 subsequent primary runoff election; to amend Section 17-13-47,
49 Code of Alabama 1975, to require political parties to publish
50 qualifications for candidates on the websites of the political
51 parties; and to make nonsubstantive, technical revisions to
52 update the existing code language to current
53 style.
54 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
55 Section 1. (a) This section shall be known and may be
56 cited as the Safeguard Alabama Voter Engagement (SAVE) Act.
Page 2

cited as the Safeguard Alabama Voter Engagement (SAVE) Act.
HB541 INTRODUCED
57 (b)(1) On and after January 1, 2027, a qualified
58 elector shall register his or her political party affiliation
59 before the elector may vote in any countywide or statewide
60 primary or primary runoff election. A qualified elector may
61 register his or her party affiliation through the Secretary of
62 State's website or with the board of registrars, or at the
63 voting precinct of the elector on the day of any countywide or
64 statewide primary or primary runoff election. An elector who
65 has not registered a political party affiliation shall be
66 considered unaffiliated for purposes of Title 17, Code of
67 Alabama 1975. Notwithstanding Section 17-3-50, Code of Alabama
68 1975, an unaffiliated elector may register a political party
69 affiliation at any time, including during the 14-day period
70 before an election.
71 (2) If an elector chooses to register party affiliation
72 at a voting precinct on primary election day or primary runoff
73 election day, the act of requesting the ballot of a specific
74 political party shall constitute party registration, and no
75 additional action shall be required of the elector.
76 (3) A qualified elector who has already registered his
77 or her political party affiliation may not change his or her
78 political party affiliation to a different political party
79 during the period beginning 60 days prior to a primary
80 election through the day of the corresponding general
81 election.
82 (c) An elector who has registered a political party
83 affiliation may change his or her status to unaffiliated at
84 any time, provided the elector may not subsequently register
Page 3

any time, provided the elector may not subsequently register
HB541 INTRODUCED
85 with a different political party during the blackout period
86 described in subdivision (b)(3).
87 (d) Nothing in this section shall be construed to
88 prohibit any state executive committee of a political party
89 from establishing the qualifications of individuals desiring
90 to become candidates for nomination to offices at a primary
91 election.
92 (e)(1) Beginning on and after July 1, 2027, signs shall
93 be posted at each polling place at a primary election and
94 primary runoff election that contains the following notice:
95 "By voting in this primary election, you have
96 registered your affiliation with a particular political party.
97 State law prohibits you from changing your political party
98 affiliation to a different political party until after the
99 general election. In the future, you may not change your party
100 affiliation within the 60-day period before any primary
101 election."
102 (2) A sign shall be posted in a clearly visible
103 location near the entrance of the polling place, and may be
104 posted in other conspicuous locations within a polling place,
105 as determined by the Secretary of State, by rule.
106 (f) The Secretary of State shall retain the following
107 voter history information for purposes of Section 17-4-38,
108 Code of Alabama 1975 for each voter:
109 (1) The party ballot requested in each primary and
110 primary runoff election held between January 1, 2017 and
111 January 1, 2027; and
112 (2) The party affiliation registered pursuant to this
Page 4

(2) The party affiliation registered pursuant to this
